-- Crude Options Volatility Falls as Futures Increase Second Day
-- B y   B a r b a r a   P o w e l l
-- 2012-03-08T21:10:23Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2012-03-08/crude-options-volatility-falls-as-futures-increase-second-day.html
Crude oil options volatility fell as
underlying futures rose a second consecutive day as  Greece  moved
closer to finalizing a debt swap, easing concern about the
regionâ€™s economy.  Implied volatility for at-the-money options expiring in
May, a measure of expected price swings in futures and a gauge
of options prices, was 28.4 as of 3:30 p.m., down from 29.5
yesterday.  Crude for April delivery rose 42 cents to settle at $106.58
a barrel on the  New York Mercantile Exchange . Since Feb. 17, the
front-month contract has traded in a range of $104.26 and
$110.55. The May contract gained 0.4 percent to $107.56 a
barrel.  The most active options in electronic trading today were
April $110 calls, with 2,508 lots changing hands at 3:51 p.m.
They fell 3 cents to 45 cents a barrel. May $100 puts, the
second-most active options, declined 24 cents to $1.51 with
1,551 lots trading. One contract covers 1,000 barrels of crude.  Calls accounted for 63 percent of electronic trading
volume.  The exchange distributes real-time data for electronic
trading and releases information the next business day on floor
trading, where the bulk of options trading occurs.  Bearish options accounted for 53 percent of the 113,168
trades from the previous session. April $95 puts were the most
actively traded, with 5,378 lots changing hands as they fell 10
cents to 6 cents a barrel. The next-most active options,
September $150 calls, rose 5 cents to 98 cents on volume of
3,928.  Open interest was highest for December $80 puts with 46,326
contracts. Next were December $150 calls with 38,627 lots and
December $100 calls with 34,926.  To contact the reporter on this story:
